re, England","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–17 March 1337":"–17 maart 1337","1273–1343":"1273–1343","1280–1337":"1280–1337","–1337":"–1337","1212–1272":"1212–1272","1240–1277":"1240–1277","1250–1343":"1250–1343","1255–1343":"1255–1343","1337":"1337","1212":"1212","17 March 1337":"17 maart 1337","1255":"1255","1277":"1277","1343":"1343","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","after 1277":"na 1277","1280":"1280","Wilton, Herefordshire, England":"Wilton, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England":"Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–17 March 1337":"–17 March 1337","1273–1343":"1273–1343","1280–1337":"1280–1337","–1337":"–1337","1212–1272":"1212–1272","1240–1277":"1240–1277","1250–1343":"1250–1343","1255–1343":"1255–1343","1337":"1337","1212":"1212","17 March 1337":"17 March 1337","1255":"1255","1277":"1277","1343":"1343","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","after 1277":"after 1277","1280":"1280","Wilton, Herefordshire, England":"Wilton, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England":"Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bassett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>basset</i> ‘of low stature’, a diminutive of <i>basse</i> ‘low, short’, either a nickname for a short person or a status name for someone of humble origins.","Altered form of French   Bessette   1 or <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2).","History: William Bassett (<i>c.</i> 1598–1667) came to Plymouth, MA, from Kent, England, in the 1620s; <i>c.</i> 1650 he moved to Duxbury and subesequently to Bridgewater. He had many prominent descendants, among them one of the earliest families on Martha's Vineyard. — The surname <i>Bassett</i> of French origin (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Armand, Adrien, Normand, Alphonse, Lucien, Cecile, Herve, Jacques, Laurent, Aime.","French: topographic name designating a small wood of birches, from Occitan <i>bès</i> ‘birch tree’ (see   Besse  ), or a habitational name from (La) Bessette, the name of several places in the southern part of France.","Alternatively, an altered form of French <b>Besset</b>: topographic name, a cognate of 1 above. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Bassett was born in Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Ralph Basset 1st Lord Basset Of Drayton and Hawise. She had at least 1 daughter with William de Heriz. She died on 17 March 1337, in Wilton, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–17 March 1337":"–17. märts 1337","1273–1343":"1273–1343","1280–1337":"1280–1337","–1337":"–1337","1212–1272":"1212–1272","1240–1277":"1240–1277","1250–1343":"1250–1343","1255–1343":"1255–1343","1337":"1337","1212":"1212","17 March 1337":"17. märts 1337","1255":"1255","1277":"1277","1343":"1343","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","after 1277":"pärast 1277","1280":"1280","Wilton, Herefordshire, England":"Wilton, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England":"Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–17 March 1337":"–17. maaliskuuta 1337","1273–1343":"1273–1343","1280–1337":"1280–1337","–1337":"–1337","1212–1272":"1212–1272","1240–1277":"1240–1277","1250–1343":"1250–1343","1255–1343":"1255–1343","1337":"1337","1212":"1212","17 March 1337":"17. maaliskuuta 1337","1255":"1255","1277":"1277","1343":"1343","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","after 1277":"1277 jälkeen","1280":"1280","Wilton, Herefordshire, England":"Wilton, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England":"Wiverton Hall, Nottinghamshire, England","Drayton Bassett, Staffordshire, England":"Drayton Bassett, Staf